@node intro Introduction

@{u}@{b}Introduction@{ub}@{uu}

SuperTV is a replacement for the TV program that comes on the Elbox Mediator
Multimedia CD. It removes the need for all those channel files, and makes using
your TV card a much more pleasant experience.

Features include:

 · Change channels with a single keypress
 · Fullscreen borderless mode
 · ARexx controllable
 · Channel buttons in the TV window border
 · MUI interface

and loads more!

@endnode

@node requi Requirements

@{u}@{b}Requirements@{ub}@{uu}

To use SuperTV, you will need:

 · A Mediator equipped Amiga
 · The Elbox Multimedia CD
 · A Voodoo card and compatible TV card
 · tv.library installed in libs
 · MUI
 · The NList and NListview MUI classes

If you want to use a pop-up menu in the TV window, you have to install
popupmenu.library v10+ (available from Aminet).

If you don't want to use the Elbox TV program, you can remove all those channel
files and C:TV, if you wish to.

@endnode

@node insta Installation

@{u}@{b}Installation@{ub}@{uu}

Installation is very simple. Once you have the Elbox TV software installed, simply
copy the SuperTV directory somewhere on your hard disk.

If someone wishes to write an install script, please e-mail me!

@endnode

@node start Getting Started

@{u}@{b}Getting Started@{ub}@{uu}

Before you run SuperTV for the first time, please check that the icon tooltypes
are set correctly. There are two main tooltypes:

"FORMAT" tooltype options are:

"NTSC M" or "NM"
"NTSC MJ" or "NMJ"
"PAL BDGHI" or "PB"
"PAL M" or "PM"
"PAL N" or "PN"
"SECAM" or "SC"
"PAL NC" or "PNC"


"REGION" tooltype options are:

"AUSTRALIA" or "AU"
"IRELAND" or "IR"
"ITALY" or "IT"
"JAPAN" or "JP"
"NEW ZEALAND" or "NZ"
"WEST EUROPE" or "EU"
"AMERICA" or "AM"
"OTHER" or "OT"

NOTE: these are DEFAULT settings. The actual channels can be any format, and all
country presets are available from the GUI.

The first time you run SuperTV, the preferences window will appear. This is
where you configure all your TV channels etc.

Lets create our first channel:

 1) Click the "Add" button undeath the channel list.
 2) Highlight the new channel that appears, and click "Edit"
 3) A TV window will appear, along with a "Channel Editor" window

If you have already configured Elbox's TV software, you can just copy the PLL
values from a channel file into the PLL box, and skip to step 8.

 4) Click the "?" button next to the PLL box. A preset window should appear.
 5) Make sure the correct region is shown in the cycle gadget and highlight the
    first channel preset in the listview. The TV window title should change from
    "Untuned" to "SuperTV".
 6) Now, with the preset window active, press the down arrow until a TV station
    appears. If you got through all the presets and didn't find a station,
    double check you have the right region selected, then make sure you have
    plugged the aerial into the TV card. If all else fails, try setting up
    Elbox's standard TV software. If you can't get a picture in either system,
    e-mail Elbox for help.
 7) Once you have found a station, close the preset window.
 8) Put the name of the station into the "Name:" box
 9) If you need to, fine tune the station with the "+" and "-" buttons next to
    the PLL box
10) Click "OK".
11) If you need to, adjust the picture settings in the main window. These will
    be the default values for all channels added, although you can add
    specific custom settings to a channel later.

Repeat steps 1-12 until all the channels are set up, then click "Save" to save
the channels to disk.

@endnode

@node tvwin The TV window

@{u}@{b}The TV window@{ub}@{uu}

The TV window has all the channels listed down the side (or as many as it can
fit). If there is room, underneath those are three extra gadgets. These are:

 "?": Brings up the preferences window
 "P": Brings up a list of pubscreens. Double-clicking one of those pubscreens
      attempts to move SuperTV to that screen.
 "F": Selects full screen mode.

If you have popupmenu v10+ installed, the right mouse button brings up a
menu where you can change the picture size, pubscreen, or toggle fullscreen
mode.

Double clicking in the TV window toggles fullscreen mode.

You can also press the following buttons:

 F1: Toggle mute on/off (doesn't work on all TV cards)
 F2: Toggle the mouse pointer on/off
 F3: Toggle full screen mode
 1-9/A-Z: Select the relevant channel
 + or right arrow: Next channel
 - or left arrow: Previous channel

@endnode

@node prefwin The Preferences window

@{u}@{b}The Preferences window@{ub}@{uu}

There are two tabs, "Settings" and "ARexx".

In the Settings tab, you can configure the following options:

  @{u}Brightness, Contrast, Hue, Saturation U, and Saturation V@{uu}

  These are the global picture settings, but they may be overrided if a channel
  has custom values defined. If the current channel shown in the TV window has
  custom picture settings, these sliders have no visible effect.

  When you create a new channel, these values are copied into the channel
  picture settings.

  @{u}Size@{uu}

  This sets the TV picture size. This is NOT the same effect as resizing the
  TV window with the resize gadget; this sets the size of the original source
  image, which is then scaled up to the size of the actual window.

  @{u}Hide Pointer@{uu}

  This has 3 options; Never, Always and Fullscreen. When set to "never", the
  mouse pointer is always visible when the TV window is active. When set to
  "fullscreen", the mousepointer is normally visible, but hidden when the
  TV window is in fullscreen mode. When set to "Always", the pointer is always
  hidden when the TV window is active.

  @{u}Remember channel@{uu}

  When this is set, SuperTV saves the channel you were watching when you quit,
  and restores it when you re-load.

  @{u}Cycle channels@{uu}

  When this is set, pressing "+", or right arrow, or executing the
  TV_INCCHANNEL arexx command on the highest channel will loop around to the
  lowest instead of stopping. It also loops from lowest to highest.

  @{u}Add@{uu}

  This creates a new channel and adds it onto the end of the channel list abov.

  @{u}Remove@{uu}

  This deletes the channel highlighted in the list above.

  @{u}Clone@{uu}

  This creates a new channel and copies the settings for the highlighted
  channel into it.

  @{u}Edit@{uu}

  Brings up a channel editor window for the highlighted channel. Double-
  clicking a channel in the channel list has the same effect.

  @{u}/\\ and \\/@{uu}

  Moves the highlighted channel up, or down in the list.

In the ARexx tab, there are 4 places where you can specify the path and
filename of an ARexx script. The "Open TV" script is executed every time
SuperTV opens the TV window, "Change Channel" is executed every time you
change the channel, "Go fullscreen" is executed when you set fullscreen
mode, and "Change pubscreen" is executed every time you change pubscreens.

  @{u}Save@{uu}

  This saves your preferences to both ENV: and ENVARC:, then closes the
  preferences window.

  @{u}Use@{uu}

  This saves your preferences to ENV:, then closes the preferences window.
  Closing the window with the close gadget has the same effect.

  @{u}Cancel@{uu}

  This reverts back to the last saved, or used, settings, and closes the
  preferences window.

@endnode

@node cedwin The channel editor window

@{u}@{b}The channel editor window@{uu}@{ub}

The channel editor window has two tabs "Channel Settings", and "Picture". In
the channel settings tab, you can configure the following settings:

  @{u}Name@{uu}

  This is the name of the channel. This appears in the channel list, and in
  the title of the TV window when that channel is selected.

  @{u}Format@{uu}

  This is the picture format of the channel. When you create a new channel,
  this is set to the default specified in the icon tooltypes.

  @{u}Source@{uu}

  This the source of TV picture, and is equivalent to the VID_SRC parameter on
  the Elbox TV program. If you need to set a custom video source, e.g. for
  colour SHVS, select "custom" and put the number in the "custom" box below.

  @{u}PLL@{uu}

  This is the tuning value for this channel. You can put the number in
  directly, or select one of the presets from the preset window. You can also
  fine-tune a channel with the "+" and "-" buttons.

  @{u}Audio source@{uu}

  This sets the audio input for this channel

The "Picture" tab allows you to configure picture settings for this channel. If
"Custom picture settings?" is set, the values in these sliders will be used,
otherwise the global values set in the preferences window will be used.

  @{u}Save@{uu}

  This copies the values in the channel editor window into the channel you are
  editing, and closes the channel editor.

  @{u}Cancel@{uu}

  This closes the channel editor window without updating the channel.

@endnode

@node presetwin The preset window

@{u}@{b}The preset window@{uu}@{ub}

The preset window contains all the preset PLLs for different regions that came
with the Elbox TV sotware. When you select a region with the cycle gadget at
the top of the window, all the presets for that region appear below. As soon as
you highlight one of these presets, its PLL is copied to the channel editor,
and the TV window is updated to the new PLL.

@endnode

@node rexx ARexx commands

@{u}@{b}ARexx commands@{uu}@{ub}

SuperTV provides an arexx port called "SUPERTV". SuperTV understands the
following ARexx commands:

TV_SETCHANNEL <channelnum>

  With this you can change the channel showing in SuperTV. <channel> is a
  number from 1 to 9, or a letter.


  Example:

  tv_setchannel 3   /* Change to channel 3 */


TV_GETCHANNEL

  This returns the channel that is currently being viewed. It will return
  either a number from 1 - 9, or a letter. If no channel is being viewed
  (none are set up), it'll return 0.


  Example:

  tv_getchannel
  say "Channel: "result


TV_INCCHANNEL

  This increments the channel. It respects the user preferences on whether
  to stop at the highest channel or loop around.


TV_DECCHANNEL

  This decrements the channel. It respects the user preferences on whether
  to stop at the lowest channel or loop around.


TV_GETCHANNELNAME

  This returns the name of the currently viewed channel.


  Example:

  tv_getchannelname
  say "You are watching "result


TV_GETPICTURESIZE

  This returns the size of the TV picture as a number from 0 to 6. This
  equates to SuperTVs picture percentages like this:


      0 - 40%
      1 - 50%
      2 - 60%
      3 - 70%
      4 - 80%
      5 - 90%
      6 - 100%


  Example:

  tv_getpicturesize
  say "Picture size: "result


TV_SETPICTURESIZE <sizecode>

  This sets the picture size, and accepts a number from 0 - 6.


  Example:

  say "setting picture size to max..."
  tv_setpicturesize 6


TV_GETPUBSCREEN

  This returns the name of the public screen on which SuperTV is running.


  Example:

  tv_getpubscreen
  say "Screen: "result


TV_SETPUBSCREEN <pubscreenname>

  This sets the name of the public screen that SuperTV should run on. It
  is not case sensitive. If the screen does not exist, SuperTV will move
  to the default pubscreen.


  Example:

  tv_setpubscreen AmIRC



TV_GETCONTRAST

  Returns the contrast level from 0 to 255


TV_SETCONTRAST <level>

  Sets the contrast level to <level>


TV_GETBRIGHTNESS

  Returns the brightness level from 0 to 255


TV_SETBRIGHTNESS <level>

  Sets the brightness level to <level>


TV_GETSATU

  Returns the U saturation level from 0 to 255


TV_SETSATU <level>

  Sets the U saturation level to <level>


TV_GETSATV

  Returns the V saturation level from 0 to 255


TV_SETSATV <level>

  Sets the V saturation level to <level>


TV_GETHUE

  Returns the hue level from 0 to 255


TV_SETHUE <level>

  Sets the hue level to <level>


TV_FULLSCREEN [ON|OFF]

  If you run it without any arguments, it returns 1 if SuperTV is in fullscreen
  mode, or 0 if it is not. Specify ON to force SuperTV to fullscreen, or OFF to
  force it to window mode.

  Example:

  /* Toggle fullscreen */

  tv_fullscreen
  if result=1 then do
    tv_fullscreen OFF
  end
  else do
    tv_fullscreen ON
  end


TV_QUIT

  Makes SuperTV quit


TV_GETX

  Returns the X position of the SuperTV window


TV_GETH

  Returns the Y position of the SuperTV window


TV_GETWIDTH

  Returns the width of the SuperTV window


TV_GETHEIGHT

  Returns the height of the SuperTV window


TV_SETWINDOW <x> <y> [<w> <h>]

  This command moves the SuperTV window, and optionally resizes it.

  Example:

  /* Move SuperTV to (100,200) */
  tv_setwindow 100 200

  /* Move SuperTV to (40,50) and resize it to 320x256 */
  tv_setwindow 40 50 320 256

TV_MUTE [ON|OFF]

  If you run it without any arguments, it returns 1 if SuperTV is muted, or 0
  if it is not. Specify ON to set mute, or zero to turn it off.
  force it to window mode.

  Example:

  /* Toggle mute */

  tv_mute
  if result=1 then do
    tv_mute OFF
  end
  else do
    tv_mute ON
  end

@endnode

@node author Contacting the author

@{u}@{b}Contacting the author@{uu}@{ub}

@{b}IMPORTANT!@{ub} BEFORE reporting any bugs, please try to reproduce the bug
in Elbox's own TV software. If the bug is present in both TV and SuperTV,
contact Elbox, as the bug is likely to be in their TV drivers.

You can contact me at: pete@shagged.org

@endnode

